    <text id="R11218543T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Union Chief of Staff Henry Halleck replies to John Pope's August, 1862, plans for
                    Jacob Cox's troops. He suggests a safer route of movement than that by Staunton,
                    VA.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>
        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    <name type="recipient">Maj.-Gen. POPE, Sperryville, Va.:</name>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1862-08-07">August 7, 1862.</date>
                        <name type="place">WASHINGTON, D. C.,</name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute/>
                </opener>
                <p>I am of opinion that the route from Covington to Harrisonburg is more safe than
                    that by Staunton. The latter seems to me very hazardous. If Jackson is
                    concentrating at Charlottesville or vicinity he probably intends to turn your
                    right flank, which will render Cox's junction with you impossible. Order as you
                    deem best, but with caution.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute/>
                    <signed>H. W. HALLECK,<lb/> Gen.-in-Chief.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
